  <Fragment slot="buying-guide">
    <BuyingGuideSection>
      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying guide: what actually helps you keep an AeroPress ratio consistent</h2>

      <h3>Grinder consistency matters more than squeezing the ratio decimal</h3>
      <p>If your grind is all over the place, your ratio math will not save you. Half the grounds will extract fast, the other half will lag behind, and the cup tastes both bitter and sour at the same time. That is why a grinder like the <a href={amazonUrl('B0833SDN8M')} rel="nofollow sponsored noopener" target="_blank">TIMEMORE Chestnut C2</a> makes such a big difference. It is not glamorous. It just gives you more even particles, which gives you more even flavor.</p>

      <h3>A scale is the fastest upgrade for ratio repeatability</h3>
      <p>If you are still measuring by scoop, that is probably the leak in your process. Beans are not identical. Some are dense, some are puffy, and the scoop lies like a bad tape measure. A small digital scale fixes that immediately. Our full <a href="/posts/coffee-brewing-ratio-guide.html">coffee brewing ratio guide</a> goes deeper on the math, but the short version is simple: weigh the dose, weigh the water, and your good cups stop feeling accidental.</p>

      <h3>Filter choice changes how a ratio tastes</h3>
      <p>Paper filters clean the cup up and usually make a looser ratio taste smoother. Metal filters keep more oil and body, which can be great with stronger brews but a little much with dark roasts. If you love concentrate-style AeroPress drinks, Prismo is worth a look. If you want less bitterness and a cleaner finish, stock up on paper filters instead. For a closer look at how bypass changes body and strength, read our <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-bypass-recipe.html">best AeroPress bypass recipe</a> guide.</p>

      <h3>Kettle control helps when you are fine-tuning roast level</h3>
      <p>Water temperature is not the star of the show, but it absolutely changes the cup. A steady kettle like the <a href={amazonUrl('B077JBQZPX')} rel="nofollow sponsored noopener" target="_blank">Fellow Stagg EKG</a> makes it easier to stay around 195°F for darker roasts and closer to 200°F or 201°F for lighter coffees. That matters when you are tweaking bitterness and sweetness in small steps instead of making wild guesses.</p>
    </BuyingGuideSection>
  </Fragment>

